net.sf.mmm.persistence.api.jpql

Interface JpqlSyntax

  • All Superinterfaces:
    JpqlConstants

    public interface JpqlSyntax
extends JpqlConstants
    This interface is (mis)used to document the syntax the Java Persistence Query Language (JPQL). JPQL is the language for statements against persistent entities independent of the mechanism used to store those entities. It is part of the Java Persistence API (JPA).
    Since:
    1.0.0
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)
    See Also:
    JPQL_STATEMENT

    • Field Detail

      • JPQL_STATEMENT

        static final JpqlSyntax JPQL_STATEMENT
        This is the root element of the JpqlSyntax and represents any statement.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        JPQL_STATEMENT ::= SELECT_STATEMENT | UPDATE_STATEMENT | DELETE_STATEMENT

      • SELECT_STATEMENT

        static final JpqlSyntax SELECT_STATEMENT
        A Select Statement in JPQL is a JPQL_STATEMENT used to search on persistent entities. It will result in a query object and will only read from the store without causing modifications.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        JpqlConstants.SELECT ::= SELECT_CLAUSE FROM_CLAUSE [ WHERE_CLAUSE] [ GROUP_BY_CLAUSE] [HAVING_CLAUSE] [ ORDER_BY_CLAUSE]

      • SELECT_CLAUSE

        static final JpqlSyntax SELECT_CLAUSE
        The actual SELECT clause of a SELECT_STATEMENT.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        SELECT_CLAUSE ::= SELECT [JpqlConstants.DISTINCT] SELECT_EXPRESSION {, SELECT_EXPRESSION } *

      • FROM_CLAUSE

        static final JpqlSyntax FROM_CLAUSE
        The actual FROM clause of a JPQL_STATEMENT.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        FROM_CLAUSE ::= JpqlConstants.FROM IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE_DECLARATION {, { IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE_DECLARATION | COLLECTION_MEMBER_DECLARATION }} *

      • SELECT_EXPRESSION

        static final JpqlSyntax SELECT_EXPRESSION
        An expression of a SELECT_CLAUSE that specifies what to select.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        SELECT_EXPRESSION ::= SINGLE_VALUED_PATH_EXPRESSION | AGGREGATE_EXPRESSION | IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE | OBJECT(IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE)| CONSTRUCTOR_EXPRESSION

      • CONSTRUCTOR_EXPRESSION

        static final JpqlSyntax CONSTRUCTOR_EXPRESSION
        An expression of a SELECT_CLAUSE that creates new transient objects using the specified constructor.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        CONSTRUCTOR_EXPRESSION ::= NEW CONSTRUCTOR_NAME( CONSTRUCTOR_ITEM {, CONSTRUCTOR_ITEM *)

      • IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE

        static final JpqlSyntax IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE
        A simple variable to use as identifier, typically called alias. It is like a variable used to identify an entity (see PersistenceEntity) or an expression in statements like FROM, JOIN, IN, etc.
        E.g. in the JPQL query "SELECT DISTINCT alias2.author FROM Magazine alias1, IN(alias1.articles) alias2" there are two aliases used:
        • alias1 is an identifier for any persistent instance of the entity Magazine
        • alias2 is an identifier for all values of the property articles of alias1

      • COLLECTION_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD

        static final JpqlSyntax COLLECTION_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD
        A COLLECTION_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD is designated by the name of an association-field in a one-to-many or a many-to-many relationship. The type of a COLLECTION_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD is a collection of values of the abstract schema type of the related entity.
        It is the name of a field/property to identify.

      • LIKE_EXPRESSION

        static final JpqlSyntax LIKE_EXPRESSION
        LIKE_EXPRESSION ::= STRING_EXPRESSION [JpqlConstants.NOT] LIKE PATTERN_VALUE [ESCAPE #escape_character]

      • PATTERN_VALUE

        static final JpqlSyntax PATTERN_VALUE
        The value of a pattern in a LIKE_EXPRESSION, e.g. '%foo%' to match any string that contains "foo".
        Unlike the more common glob-patterns (typically used and expected by end-users) SQL has its own syntax that is also used in JPQL. The following table explains the two pattern styles.
        Wildcard Glob SQL
        Any substring (zero or more characters). * %
        A single character. ? _
        Any single character out of the given list. <not supported> [<characters>]
        Any single character NOT in the given list. <not supported> [^<characters>]
        or [!<characters>]

BETWEEN_EXPRESSION ::= ARITHMETIC_EXPRESSION [JpqlConstants.NOT] BETWEEN ARITHMETIC_EXPRESSION JpqlConstants.AND ARITHMETIC_EXPRESSION | STRING_EXPRESSION [ JpqlConstants.NOT] JpqlConstants.BETWEEN STRING_EXPRESSION JpqlConstants.AND STRING_EXPRESSION | DATETIME_EXPRESSION [ JpqlConstants.NOT] JpqlConstants.BETWEEN DATETIME_EXPRESSION JpqlConstants.AND DATETIME_EXPRESSION

      • DELETE_STATEMENT

        static final JpqlSyntax DELETE_STATEMENT
        A DELETE statement in JPQL is a JPQL_STATEMENT used to delete persistent entities. It is similar to a SELECT_STATEMENT but will delete the results instead of returning them.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        DELETE_STATEMENT ::= DELETE_CLAUSE [ WHERE_CLAUSE]

      • DELETE_CLAUSE

        static final JpqlSyntax DELETE_CLAUSE
        The actual DELETE clause of a DELETE_STATEMENT.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        DELETE_CLAUSE ::= DELETE JpqlConstants.FROM ABSTRACT_SCHEMA_NAME [[ JpqlConstants.AS] IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE]

      • ABSTRACT_SCHEMA_NAME

        static final JpqlSyntax ABSTRACT_SCHEMA_NAME
        The name (typically Class.getSimpleName()) of an Entity (see PersistenceEntity).

      • UPDATE_STATEMENT

        static final JpqlSyntax UPDATE_STATEMENT
        An UPDATE statement in JPQL is a JPQL_STATEMENT used to delete persistent entities. It is similar to a SELECT_STATEMENT but will update the results instead of returning them.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        UPDATE_STATEMENT ::= UPDATE_CLAUSE [WHERE_CLAUSE]

      • UPDATE_CLAUSE

        static final JpqlSyntax UPDATE_CLAUSE
        The actual UPDATE clause of an UPDATE_STATEMENT.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        UPDATE_CLAUSE ::= JpqlConstants.UPDATE ABSTRACT_SCHEMA_NAME [[JpqlConstants.AS] IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE] JpqlConstants.SET UPDATE_ITEM {, UPDATE_ITEM} *

      • UPDATE_ITEM

        static final JpqlSyntax UPDATE_ITEM
        An update assignment of a single item in a UPDATE_CLAUSE.
        The BNF definition is as following:
        UPDATE_ITEM ::= [IDENTIFICATION_VARIABLE.]{STATE_FIELD | SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD = NEW_VALUE

      • STATE_FIELD

        static final JpqlSyntax STATE_FIELD
        A navigation path to a field or property of an entity. STATE_FIELD ::= {EMBEDDED_CLASS_STATE_FIELD.}* SIMPLE_STATE_FIELD

      • SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD

        static final JpqlSyntax SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD
        A SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD is designated by the name of an association-field in a one-to-one or many-to-one relationship. The type of a SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_FIELD and thus a SINGLE_VALUED_ASSOCIATION_PATH_EXPRESSION is the abstract schema type of the related entity.
        It is the name of a field/property to identify.

      • SIMPLE_STATE_FIELD

        static final JpqlSyntax SIMPLE_STATE_FIELD

      • EMBEDDED_CLASS_STATE_FIELD

        static final JpqlSyntax EMBEDDED_CLASS_STATE_FIELD
        An EMBEDDED_CLASS_STATE_FIELD is designated by the name of an entity-state field that corresponds to an embedded class. Navigation to a related entity results in a value of the related entity's abstract schema type.
        See Also:
        Embeddable
